Is the difference between infant mortality rates in blacks and whites still improving? A look back at the past ten years

Corinne A Riddell, PhD

Sam Harper, PhD

Jay S Kaufman, PhD

Department of Epidemiology, Biostatistics and Occupational Health, McGill University, Montreal, Canada.

Address correspondence to: Corinne Riddell, PhD, Department of Epidemiology, Biostatistics & Occupational Health, McGill University, 1020 Pine Avenue West, Room 36B, Montreal, QC H3A 1A2, Canada. Email: corinne.riddell@mail.mcgill.ca

Current word count (text only, exclusive of title, references, and tables): XXX Date of last revision: Dec XX, 2016

Introduction

Infant mortality decreased by 16% for infants born to non-Hispanic black women between 2005 and 2011 and 12% for infants born to non-Hispanic white women over the same time period.1 During this time, mortality declined for each of the top four causes of death.1 Understanding whether infant mortality has continued to decline since 2011, and whether the difference between blacks and whites continued to narrow will provide an important gauge of the United States progress towards reducing racial inequality.

Methods

We abstracted data on deaths and population among infants (< 1 years old) from the US National Vital Statistics System by cause of death and race for 2005-2015. We limited our analysis to non-hispanic black and white infants.2 The overall rate of infant mortality was calculated as the number of deaths divided by the population size, according to race, year and cause of death. We calculate these rates for the top four causes of infant death and for a residual category encapsulating all other causes. The excess risk of infant mortality in blacks was calculated as the absolute difference between the rates in blacks and whites. We do not include confidence intervals, as these rates are not subject to sampling error. R version 3.2.4 was used to conduct this analysis. No ethical review was required since this study used de-identified data.

Results

From 2005 to 2012, the infant mortality rate for non-hispanic blacks decreased from 14.3 to 11.1 per 1,000 infants (Figure 1). Thereafter, the infant mortality rate in blacks plateaued, with two of the past three years seeing slight increases to the rate of infant mortality. For non-hispanic whites, the infant mortality rate decreased from 5.9 to 4.9 per 1,000 infants from 2005 to 2015 and experienced no years of increasing rates. Because the black infant mortality rate declined faster than the white rate, the excess risk in blacks fell from 8.4 excess deaths per 1,000 infants in 2005 to 6.0 excess deaths per 1,000 in 2012. Thereafter, excess risk rose slightly to 6.3 in 2015.

An excess risk of 6.3 deaths per 1,000 infants implies nearly 4,000 excess infant deaths among blacks compared to the amount of deaths that would have occurred had they experienced the mortality rate among whites. To arrive at this number, the black infant mortality rate that occurred can be calculated as 6907/614972, the number of deaths and population size among black infants in 2015. To calculate excess deaths, we then apply the rate of mortality among white infants (4.9 per 1,000) to the black population, and see that 3041 black infants would have died rather than 6907 an excess of 3866 infant deaths. If the rate of death was held at its 2014 level (6698 deaths to 608099 infants), 133 fewer black infant deaths would have occurred.

COD-specific (Figure 2 findings to write up properly)

-the most frequent cause of infant death among blacks is short gest/LBW, which is also the causes with the largest absolute and relative difference between blacks and whites. -from 2005 to 2011, sustained progress in reducing deaths related to short gestation/LBW among blacks, working towards narrowing the gap. Plateauing in recent years.

-The next most frequent cause of death among blacks is congenital malformations, which also underwent progress towards lowering deaths related to congential malformations between 2005 and 2012, followed by a plateau

-Rates of deaths related to SIDS and maternal complications are the remaining two top causes of infant death in blacks and again exhibit a pattern of early decreases followed by a plateau period.

-Infant deaths from all other causes capture all remaining deaths and again show this pattern on early declines followed by plateau and slight increase.
